   <titles>
      <title>Preview: Properties of Linear Transformations</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here are two basic properties which are specific to linear transformations and are not enjoyed by every transformation.</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol type="1">
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A linear transformation <math>
                           <latex>f\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> sends the <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>-vector of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> to the <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>-vector of <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math>; in symbols: <math>
                           <latex>f(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A linear transformation <math>
                           <latex>f\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> transforms any linear motion in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                        </math> into a linear motion in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
            </ol>
            <para>
               <para.body>The first property is frequently helpful in detecting non-linear maps. The second property explains the name "linear transformations".</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
